MCC Board Support Library

Microchip produces development boards which are used by customers to jump start their designs. MCC Board Support Library allows the users to easily configure and generate the code for the selected board of their choice without going through lot of documentation. Board Support Library helps in auto configuration of the Pins and Peripheral modules present in the development board.

More Information

Code Configurator Library v1.29.3(Beta Release)

The Code Configurator Library(CCL) provides devices and modules which are developed to enable easy device migration and configuration of modules. To learn more about the bundle of libraries and modules offered in the CCL, please refer the below "Libraries Bundled" section.

What's new

This is the first release of the Code Configurator Library (CCL), supporting module dependencies with other modules.

System Requirements

  • MPLAB® X IDE v5.45 or newer
  • MPLAB® Code Configurator v4.0.1 or newer

Installing Code Configurator Library(CCL)

    1. First install the MPLAB® Code Configurator Plugin(MCC):

  • In MPLAB X IDE, click on Tools → Plugin
  • Click on Available Plugins tab
  • Check the box for the MPLAB® Code Configurator, and click on Install
  • Close and re-launch MPLAB X after installation.

    2. To install the Code Configurator Library(CCL):

  • Launch the MCC.
  • Go to the MCC Versions panel.
  • Go to "Code Configurator Library" under Libraries->Microchip Technology, Inc->Software
  • Select the version of the "Code Configurator Library" which needs to be installed, right click and Mark for load.
  • Click on "Load Selected Libraries" button on the MCC Versions panel.

Libraries Bundled

    Table of contents

    1 16-Bit Data EEPROM Emulation Library(DEE)
    2 FLASH

  • 16-Bit Data EEPROM Emulation Library(DEE) v1.0.4

    • Summary:

    Microchip Technology Inc. offers a wide variety of cost-effective PIC24 MCUs and dsPIC33 DSCs with only the internal Flash memory. Many applications store nonvolatile information in the Flash program memory using table read and write operations. Applications that need to frequently update this data may have greater endurance requirements than the specified Flash endurance. The alternate solution of using an external, serial EEPROM device may not be appropriate for cost-sensitive or pin-constrained applications. This library offers a cost-effective solution that addresses these issues. The 16-Bit Data EEPROM Emulation Library features an interface similar to an internal data EEPROM, which uses the available Flash program memory and offers endurance improvement by a factor of up to 500 . This library provides an easy to configure user interface using which the DEE library can be configured easily and quickly.

    What's new

    This is the first release of the 16-Bit Data EEPROM Emulation Library.

    Features Added:

    • This library provides the user interface to configure the Data EEPROM Emulation detailed in the App note AN1095 (https://www.microchip.com/wwwAppNotes/AppNotes.aspx?appnote=en530593) .

    Bugs Fixed:

    • NA

    Deviation from AN1095:

    • In this library there is a slight deviation regarding the handling of DEE_Write() routine , when the DEE_Write() routine is called with no space left in the flash page(this mostly happens when there is a reset during Pack operation) AN1095 mentions that packSkipped status will be returned and users have to explicitly call the Pack operation. But in this library , Pack operation is automatically called by the DEE_Write() routine when there is no space left in the current page and DEE_Write() will continue normally after Pack operation.

    Devices Supported:

    All 16 bit device families supported by pic24-dspic33-pic32mm library version 1.169.2 except the PIC24F-K series of devices.

  • FLASH v1.0.3

    Under the MCC Device Resources panel, two "FLASH" modules may be shown, one from the pic24/dspic/pic32mm device library and the other from the Code Configurator Library. Users are recommended to use the FLASH module from the pic24/dspic/pic32mm device library if they just want to use the FLASH module. The 16-Bit Data EEPROM Emulation Library (DEE) uses the FLASH module from the Code Configurator Library.

    The current MCC Bootloader depends on FLASH from the pic24/dspic/pic32mm device library.

MCC X2CScope Library Summary

X2CScope is a lightweight firmware based debugging tool, and it is running on the target MCU parallel to the application. It is a runtime online debugging tool that works in RUN and DEBUGGING mode. X2CScope is for generic use in any application and perfectly fits motor control applications.

The Scope plug-in features a Variable Monitor which continuously reads variable(s) from the target and displays the data as numeric value(s). The plug-in also contains an oscilloscope-like GUI including features like channel- & trigger configuration for up to 2 channels and an offset- & gain set-up for each channel.

More Information

Refer to the release notes above for the list of supported devices and a more in-depth description.

MCC Melody Summary

MCC Melody provides the following features:

  1. Allows modules to be graphically linked together (See more about Application Builder).
  2. Allows modules to be available in web clients, as well as desktop clients.
  3. Allows modules to be migrated from one device to other.

This library not only provides above features, it also delivers devices and modules (See more details in Libraries and Modules section).

System Requirements

Melody is supported in both online and offline environments.

Online System Requirements

  • Environment
    • MPLAB® Xpress IDE
  • Supported Browsers
    • Google Chrome
    • Mozilla Firefox
    • Internet Explorer
    • Safari

Offline System Requirements

  • Environment
    • MPLAB® X IDE v5.45 or later
    • MPLAB® XC8 Compiler v2.31 or later
    • MCC Plugin v4.1.0 or later
    • MCC Core v5.1.0 or later

Supported Operating Systems

  • Windows OS
  • Linux OS
  • MAC OS

Installation Requirements

Online Melody

No additional installations needed for MPLAB® Xpress IDE Environment.

Offline Melody

To use Melody offline, both the MCC Plugin and the Melody Library should be installed.

  • To install the MPLAB® Code Configurator Plugin:
    1. In the MPLAB® X IDE, select Plugins from the Tools menu.
    2. Select the Available Plugins tab.
    3. Tick the checkbox for the MPLAB® Code Configurator, and click on Install.
  • To install the Melody Library:
    1. Navigate to the MPLAB® Code Configurator webpage.
    2. Download Melody (melody-x.y.z.mc3lib).
    3. In the MPLAB® X IDE, select Options from the Tools menu.
    4. Click on Plugins.
    5. Click on Install Library.
    6. Browse to the location where you saved the .mc3lib file, select and click Open.
    7. Restart MPLAB® X IDE.
  • To load a different Melody library version:
    1. In MPLAB X® IDE, go to the menu toolbar and select Tools > Embedded > MPLAB® Code Configurator.
    2. Once MCC is loaded, go to the Versions tab (lower left of the default screen).
    3. Go to Libraries > Microchip Technology, Inc. > Software > Melody. The currently loaded Melody library version is marked with a green tick.
    4. Right click on your required version and select Mark for Load.
    5. Click the Load Selected Libraries button to load the library.

What's New in MCC Melody

Application Builder

The Application Builder provides graphical view of the peripherals, drivers, and libraries being used in the project. It allows users to see how a system hardware or a peripheral hardware present in the micro-controller is connected to various peripheral implementations, drivers and libraries. It also shows any inter dependencies between them.

Module Configuration UI Updates

Module configuration UI is moved to the right column instead of being present in the center column. This allows users to see other views such as Application Builder in the center column.

Pin Manager Updates

Earlier Pin Manager is renamed to Pins.

Pins View
  • Columns now support additional pin attributes based on individual device families of PIC and AVR (i.e., Location, Slew Rate, Input Level Control).
  • Pin attribute headers are made more descriptive (e.g. OD > Open Drain, WPU > Weak Pullup).
  • Location attribute column is added that shows the physical pin location in the package.
  • Sorting of column headers is provided for necessary attributes like Location, Pin Name, Module, Function.
Pins Package View
  • The position is changed to bottom left, adjacent to Versions Panel.
  • Package can now be changed from both Package View as well as Grid View.
  • Mouse scroll supports smooth zoom in/out.
  • Secondary/Right click supports panning/drag.
  • Additional Zoom-In/Out buttons provided in toolbar for easy navigation and step-wise zoom.
Pins Grid View
  • Tooltip is made dynamic that gives useful information for guiding the user.
  • By default, Locked Pins Tooltip highlights the API name.
  • User is allowed to make any pin selection. If conflicting selection is made, it’ll be notified under Notifications Tab.

Device Resources and Project Resources Updates

Generic Updates

The order of grouping is changed from the previous versions. All the groups are still present, but the libraries and drivers are moved above peripherals.

Hardware Peripherals and Driver Category Updates

Peripheral Category now contains only register view configuration, and will generate only initialization function.

Driver Category contains configurable UI that generate driver code for different microcontroller peripherals (only 8-bit is supported for this release).

Generated Code Updates
File NameWhat is in the file
systemAll the system peripherals are generated here.
system/system.hAPI for initializing the peripheral, drivers, and middleware in the project. This file is called from main.c
system/src/system.cCode for initializing the peripheral, drivers, and middleware in the project. The SYSTEM_Initialize() function initializes the MCU system(oscillators, clocks, flash wait states, etc.) and peripherals, which have been selected.
system/clock.hAPI for initializing the clock registers. Automatically called from SYSTEM_Initialize()
system/interrupt.hImplementations for global interrupt handling. For individual peripheral handlers, please refer to peripheral driver.
system/pins.hAPI for initializing the pins. Automatically called from SYSTEM_Initialize()
system/src/pins.cCode for initializing pins.
driver folderEach driver will have dedicated folder name, which represents the abstract behavior of the peripheral (ex: uart, adc).

Libraries and Modules

Please refer to the Melody Release Notes.

MCC X2C Library Summary

The X2C MCC library purpose is to help to create an X2C based project structure. The module creates the necessary framework files and model files. The X2C framework provides an easy model driven software development method, which is a good tool to create complex control algorithms, build complex mathematical systems and for fast prototyping.

More Information
